  <content>
    <title>Fine-tuning (LoRA)</title>

    <summary>Parameter-efficient fine-tuning of LLMs using LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation) and its variants (QLoRA, DoRA, rsLoRA). LoRA trains small adapter layers (rank r) instead of updating all weights, reducing memory 10-20x while retaining 90-95% of full fine-tuning quality. Target all linear layers (q_proj, k_proj, v_proj, o_proj, gate_proj, up_proj, down_proj), start with r=16, alpha=32, and mix 20-30% general data to prevent catastrophic forgetting.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Full fine-tuning of 70B+ models requires A100/H100 clusters. LoRA makes fine-tuning accessible: QLoRA can fine-tune a 7B model on 8-12GB VRAM (consumer GPU). The adapter size is tiny (~65K parameters for r=8 on a 4096-dim layer), making multi-adapter serving and rollback practical. DoRA improves over LoRA by decomposing weights into magnitude and direction components, achieving near-full fine-tuning quality on complex tasks.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Need consistent domain-specific terminology or jargon the base model handles inconsistently</item>
        <item>Output format must be exact and reliable (JSON schema, medical codes, proprietary syntax)</item>
        <item>Inference cost reduction: fine-tuned models need shorter system prompts</item>
        <item>You have 500+ quality labeled examples in the target distribution</item>
        <item>Style/brand voice consistency required at high volume</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fewer than 100 quality examples — few-shot prompting will outperform</item>
        <item>Requirements are changing — fine-tuned model becomes a liability when task evolves</item>
        <item>Need real-time knowledge — fine-tuning bakes in a snapshot; use RAG for live data</item>
        <item>No GPU access and limited budget — OpenAI fine-tuning API is a better path</item>
        <item>Model must handle wildly different tasks — specialized adapter degrades generality</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="how-lora-works">
      <p>LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation) freezes the original weights W and trains two small matrices B and A such that the adapted weights W' = W + BA. Rank r controls the size of B (d×r) and A (r×k). At inference, the delta BA is merged into W — no extra latency.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use r=16, alpha=32 as starting defaults for most fine-tuning tasks. This provides stable training dynamics (alpha/r=2 scaling) without overfitting on small datasets.</statement>
        <rationale>r=16 captures enough task-specific signal for most NLP tasks. Setting alpha=2r scales the LoRA output appropriately — values much lower than 1 cause the adapter to underfit; values much higher cause instability. Empirically, r=16/alpha=32 is the most robust starting point before task-specific tuning.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Target modules: always include q_proj and v_proj. For better quality add k_proj, o_proj, and gate_proj/up_proj/down_proj (MLP). Never add lm_head — it causes catastrophic output format corruption.</statement>
        <rationale>Attention projection matrices carry the most task-specific information. Adding MLP projections improves quality at the cost of more trainable parameters. The lm_head controls token probabilities directly — fine-tuning it frequently breaks output formatting and requires much more data.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="technique-comparison">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use QLoRA (4-bit NF4 quantization + LoRA) when GPU VRAM is under 24GB. Use full LoRA (bf16) when VRAM allows. Use DoRA when initial fine-tuning quality is below baseline with standard LoRA. Use rsLoRA when r &gt; 32.</statement>
        <rationale>QLoRA enables 70B model fine-tuning on a single A100 80GB or two 24GB GPUs. DoRA (Weight-Decomposed LoRA) decomposes updates into magnitude and direction components, outperforming LoRA on low-data regimes at the cost of ~10% more compute. rsLoRA scales the LoRA output by 1/sqrt(r) rather than 1/r, stabilizing training when using high ranks.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>LoRA: bf16, r=16/alpha=32, no quantization; requires full VRAM for base model; fastest training</item>
        <item>QLoRA: 4-bit NF4 base + bf16 adapter; 60-70% VRAM reduction; 10-20% slower training; minimal quality loss</item>
        <item>DoRA: decomposes magnitude+direction; better on &lt;500 examples; 10% more compute; use when LoRA underperforms baseline</item>
        <item>rsLoRA: 1/sqrt(r) scaling; use when r &gt; 32; prevents gradient vanishing at high ranks</item>
      </list>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from peft import LoraConfig, TaskType

# Standard LoRA defaults
lora_config = LoraConfig(
    task_type=TaskType.CAUSAL_LM,
    r=16,
    lora_alpha=32,
    lora_dropout=0.05,
    target_modules=["q_proj", "v_proj", "k_proj", "o_proj"],
    bias="none",
)

# QLoRA: add BitsAndBytesConfig to model loading
from transformers import BitsAndBytesConfig
bnb_config = BitsAndBytesConfig(
    load_in_4bit=True,
    bnb_4bit_quant_type="nf4",
    bnb_4bit_compute_dtype="bfloat16",
    bnb_4bit_use_double_quant=True,
)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="hardware-requirements">
      <list>
        <item>7B model, full LoRA (bf16): 1× A100 40GB</item>
        <item>7B model, QLoRA (4-bit): 1× RTX 3090/4090 24GB</item>
        <item>13B model, QLoRA: 1× A100 40GB or 2× RTX 3090</item>
        <item>70B model, QLoRA: 2× A100 80GB (tensor parallel) or 4× A100 40GB</item>
        <item>Mixtral 8×7B, QLoRA: 2× A100 80GB (active expert routing)</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Enable gradient checkpointing and set per_device_train_batch_size=1 with gradient_accumulation_steps=4-8 when VRAM is tight. This simulates batch size 4-8 without storing all intermediate activations simultaneously.</statement>
        <rationale>Gradient checkpointing recomputes intermediate activations during backprop instead of storing them, trading compute for memory. For LoRA fine-tuning, the dominant VRAM consumer is activations — checkpointing can free 40-60% of activation VRAM at ~20% throughput cost.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="rank-selection">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set r by task complexity: r=4 for style/format tasks, r=8 for domain adaptation, r=16 for instruction following, r=32-64 for large behavioral shifts. Validate with eval: if loss plateau occurs early, increase r; if overfitting, decrease r.</statement>
        <rationale>Rank is the bottleneck of representational capacity for the adapter. Style tasks require minimal new representations; behavioral rewrites require higher rank. Going beyond r=64 rarely helps for most tasks and increases parameter count significantly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="hyperparameter-selection">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use learning_rate=2e-4 for QLoRA and 1e-4 for full LoRA as starting points. Apply cosine learning rate schedule with 3-5% warmup steps. Do not use linear decay — it converges slower and overshoots the minimum on small datasets.</statement>
        <rationale>LoRA adapters have fewer parameters than full fine-tuning, so they can tolerate higher learning rates. QLoRA's 4-bit base weights have different gradient behavior — 2e-4 compensates for quantization noise. Cosine decay provides smooth convergence and avoids the sharp drop of linear decay that causes instability in the final training phase.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from transformers import TrainingArguments

training_args = TrainingArguments(
    output_dir="./checkpoints",
    num_train_epochs=3,
    per_device_train_batch_size=1,
    gradient_accumulation_steps=8,    # effective batch size = 8
    learning_rate=2e-4,               # QLoRA default
    lr_scheduler_type="cosine",
    warmup_ratio=0.03,                # 3% warmup
    bf16=True,                        # bf16 for adapter weights
    gradient_checkpointing=True,
    logging_steps=10,
    save_strategy="epoch",
    eval_strategy="epoch",
    load_best_model_at_end=True,
)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="data-quality-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Minimum 200 examples to see measurable improvement; 1,000+ for reliable task specialization. Below 100 examples, use few-shot prompting instead. Quality gates: no duplicate examples (exact or near-duplicate), no truncated outputs, no mismatched instruction-response pairs.</statement>
        <rationale>Transformers learn patterns from repetition. Below 100 examples, the model memorizes rather than generalizes. Duplicate examples inflate validation metrics while degrading real-world performance. Truncated outputs (cut at max_length mid-sentence) teach the model incomplete patterns that surface at inference.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Format all training examples in the same chat template as the target inference setup. Mismatch between training and inference format is the most common cause of degraded fine-tuned model quality.</statement>
        <rationale>Chat templates (ChatML, Llama-3 template, Mistral template) add special tokens that the model uses to identify roles. If training uses raw text and inference uses a chat template, the model sees tokens it was never trained to produce, causing incoherent completions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from trl import SFTTrainer, DataCollatorForCompletionOnlyLM

# Only train on completion tokens, not the instruction
response_template = "<|assistant|>"
collator = DataCollatorForCompletionOnlyLM(response_template, tokenizer=tokenizer)

trainer = SFTTrainer(
    model=model,
    tokenizer=tokenizer,
    train_dataset=train_dataset,
    data_collator=collator,
    dataset_text_field="text",
    max_seq_length=2048,
    args=training_args,
    peft_config=lora_config,
)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="catastrophic-forgetting-prevention">
      <rule>
        <statement>Mix 20-30% general instruction data (e.g., Alpaca, FLAN) into domain-specific training data. Eval on both domain and general benchmarks after training. If general benchmark drops more than 5%, reduce domain data ratio.</statement>
        <rationale>Fine-tuning on a narrow task overwrites general capabilities. The model "forgets" how to follow general instructions, perform reasoning outside the training domain, or maintain output format. Mixing general data acts as a regularizer — the model must maintain general performance while learning the new task.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use early stopping with patience=3 epochs. Monitor validation loss on the domain dataset; halt when it stops improving. Never train for a fixed number of epochs without monitoring — overfitting degrades generalization silently.</statement>
        <rationale>LoRA adapters can overfit small datasets within 3-5 epochs. The training loss continues to decrease even as the validation loss starts rising. Without early stopping, the final checkpoint is the most overfitted — not the best. Load the best checkpoint (lowest validation loss) at the end.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="eval-gate">
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not deploy a fine-tuned model without passing a quality gate: (1) task-specific accuracy above baseline + 10%, (2) general instruction following score above 80% of base model, (3) no refusal on in-distribution prompts (&gt;95% response rate). Block deployment if any gate fails.</statement>
        <rationale>Fine-tuned models frequently degrade in unexpected ways: they become more refusal-prone, lose general formatting, or hallucinate domain entities not present in training data. Without explicit gates, degraded models reach production and harm user trust. The baseline+10% threshold prevents deploying a fine-tuned model that underperforms the original.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def eval_gate(model, tokenizer, domain_eval, general_eval, base_scores):
    domain_acc = evaluate_domain(model, tokenizer, domain_eval)
    general_score = evaluate_general(model, tokenizer, general_eval)
    refusal_rate = measure_refusal_rate(model, tokenizer, domain_eval)

    assert domain_acc >= base_scores["domain"] + 0.10, \
        f"Domain accuracy {domain_acc:.2f} below threshold {base_scores['domain']+0.10:.2f}"
    assert general_score >= base_scores["general"] * 0.80, \
        f"General score {general_score:.2f} degraded below 80% of base {base_scores['general']:.2f}"
    assert refusal_rate <= 0.05, \
        f"Refusal rate {refusal_rate:.2%} exceeds 5% threshold"
    return True
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="production-pipeline">
      <rule>
        <statement>Implement the training pipeline as: validate data → submit training job → poll status → run eval gate → merge adapter → deploy. Never merge an adapter that has not passed the eval gate. Never skip data validation before submission.</statement>
        <rationale>Automated pipelines without validation silently train on malformed data, consuming GPU hours and producing unusable models. The eval gate must run before merging because merged weights cannot be easily separated — a failed merge requires re-training from the base model.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def run_lora_pipeline(dataset_path: str, output_dir: str) -> str:
    # 1. Validate data before GPU time
    validate_jsonl(dataset_path)

    # 2. Train
    trainer = build_trainer(dataset_path, output_dir)
    trainer.train()

    # 3. Eval gate: fail fast before merge
    base_scores = load_base_scores()
    eval_gate(trainer.model, trainer.tokenizer,
              domain_eval=DOMAIN_EVAL, general_eval=GENERAL_EVAL,
              base_scores=base_scores)

    # 4. Merge adapter into base model
    merged_model = trainer.model.merge_and_unload()
    merged_model.save_pretrained(f"{output_dir}/merged")

    # 5. Return merged path for serving
    return f"{output_dir}/merged"
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="adapter-merging">
      <rule>
        <statement>Call merge_and_unload() to fold LoRA weights into the base model before serving. Do not serve with the adapter loaded on top of the base — it adds 10-20ms overhead per token and requires shipping two artifacts.</statement>
        <rationale>Serving with an unmerged adapter requires loading both the base model and the adapter, adding memory overhead and latency per forward pass. After merging, the model is a single artifact with the same size as the base model and no inference overhead. The adapter can always be re-applied from training checkpoints if needed.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Keep the original base model weights and adapter checkpoints separately. Do not delete adapter checkpoints after merging. If the merged model fails production eval, re-train from the base model — do not attempt to reverse-engineer the adapter from the merged weights.</statement>
        <rationale>Merging is irreversible. Adapter extraction from merged weights produces approximate, lower-quality adapters. The base model + adapter checkpoint is the safe restore point for any rollback scenario.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="rollback-strategy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Deploy fine-tuned models behind an A/B routing layer. Send 5% of traffic to the fine-tuned model; keep 95% on the production baseline. Gate full traffic shift on: P50 latency within 10% of baseline, error rate below 0.1%, domain accuracy above gate threshold from live traffic sample.</statement>
        <rationale>Fine-tuned models can exhibit distribution shift on real production traffic that is not captured in eval datasets. Gradual rollout limits blast radius. The 10% latency gate catches merged model quantization mismatches that increase inference time.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>lora_dropout=0 at inference: PEFT sets dropout to 0 automatically in eval mode; do not manually set it — overriding breaks the saved config</item>
        <item>BFloat16 vs Float16: use bf16=True, not fp16=True, for modern GPUs (A100, H100, RTX 3090+); fp16 causes numeric overflow on long sequences</item>
        <item>Gradient checkpointing + custom attention: not all models support gradient checkpointing with custom attention implementations; test before long training runs</item>
        <item>Max sequence length: set max_seq_length to P99 of your training data length, not the model's maximum; padding to model max wastes VRAM and slows training</item>
        <item>PEFT version pinning: PEFT API changes between minor versions; pin to a specific version in requirements and test before upgrades</item>
        <item>DeepSpeed ZeRO-3 + PEFT: not all PEFT configs are compatible with ZeRO-3; use ZeRO-2 for multi-GPU LoRA training unless specifically tested</item>
      </list>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Training on the full conversation history including previous assistant turns as loss targets.</description>
        <reason>Including previous assistant turns in the loss function teaches the model to predict its own prior outputs, which creates self-reinforcing patterns and increases hallucination. Use DataCollatorForCompletionOnlyLM to mask all tokens except the final assistant response.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A subagent orchestrates the fine-tuning pipeline: it generates a config from a template (Axolotl or Unsloth YAML), submits a training job to a GPU cloud (Modal, RunPod, Lambda), polls for completion, downloads the adapter checkpoint, runs an automated eval, and gates deployment on a passing score threshold. Human review is required before pushing a merged model to production inference.</p>

      <note>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent — manages training job lifecycle and eval gates in SDD-style task loop</note>

      <note>Prompt pattern: Given the dataset path, base model, and hardware constraints below, output a valid Axolotl YAML config. Set lora_r, lora_alpha, learning_rate, and num_epochs based on dataset size. Include validation split.</note>

      <note>Minimal PEFT LoRA training stub (Unsloth path):
from unsloth import FastLanguageModel
model, tokenizer = FastLanguageModel.from_pretrained(
    model_name="unsloth/llama-3-8b-bnb-4bit",
    max_seq_length=2048,
    load_in_4bit=True,
)
model = FastLanguageModel.get_peft_model(
    model,
    r=16,
    lora_alpha=32,
    target_modules=["q_proj","k_proj","v_proj","o_proj","gate_proj","up_proj","down_proj"],
    use_rslora=False,
    use_gradient_checkpointing="unsloth",
)
      </note>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>peft: LoRA/QLoRA/DoRA adapter API. Install: pip install peft. Docs: huggingface.co/docs/peft</item>
        <item>trl: SFT, DPO, ORPO trainers. Install: pip install trl. Docs: huggingface.co/docs/trl</item>
        <item>unsloth: 2x speed, 80% less VRAM. Install: pip install unsloth. Docs: unsloth.ai</item>
        <item>axolotl: YAML-config-driven training. Install: pip install axolotl. Docs: github.com/OpenAccess-AI-Collective/axolotl</item>
        <item>llama-factory: WebUI + CLI training. Install: pip install llamafactory. Docs: github.com/hiyouga/LLaMA-Factory</item>
        <item>mergekit: Merge LoRA adapters into base. Install: pip install mergekit. Docs: github.com/arcee-ai/mergekit</item>
        <item>lm-eval: Harness for standardized evals. Install: pip install lm-eval. Docs: github.com/EleutherAI/lm-evaluation-harness</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Modal (SaaS): GPU cloud with Python SDK; ideal for agent-triggered training jobs</item>
        <item>RunPod (SaaS): On-demand A100/H100; REST API for pod lifecycle</item>
        <item>Lambda Cloud (SaaS): Per-hour GPU; cheaper for long runs</item>
        <item>Hugging Face AutoTrain (SaaS): Web UI + API; limited config flexibility</item>
        <item>Vast.ai (SaaS): Spot GPU market; cheapest option, less reliable SLA</item>
        <item>Weights &amp; Biases (SaaS): Training tracking; agent reads metrics via W&amp;B API for eval gates</item>
        <item>MLflow (OSS): Self-hosted experiment tracking; log adapter artifacts and metrics</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agent must not auto-deploy an adapter without a passing eval gate — always gate on quantitative threshold</item>
        <item>GPU cloud spot instances can be preempted mid-training; configure Axolotl checkpointing every 100 steps</item>
        <item>Training job APIs (Modal, RunPod) are async — agent must poll with backoff, not block synchronously</item>
        <item>W&amp;B API key must be present in agent environment before training starts; missing key silently skips logging</item>
        <item>Adapter VRAM footprint is small, but inference of merged model requires full base model VRAM — size accordingly</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint required when deploying fine-tuned model to production serving (it may behave unexpectedly on out-of-distribution inputs)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Target all linear layers (q_proj, k_proj, v_proj, o_proj, gate_proj, up_proj, down_proj) for best coverage</item>
        <item>Start with r=16, alpha=32; increase r only if validation loss plateaus after 2 epochs</item>
        <item>Mix 20-30% general instruction data with task-specific data to prevent catastrophic forgetting</item>
        <item>Use rsLoRA (use_rslora=True) when r&gt;64 to avoid gradient instability</item>
        <item>Validate data quality manually: sample 50 examples before submitting any training job</item>
        <item>Track training and validation loss separately — diverging val loss after epoch 2 means overfit</item>
        <item>Save adapter only (not merged weights) until eval passes; merged weights are harder to rollback</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/lora-config.py" purpose="LoRAConfig dataclass and LoRATrainingPipeline production class"/>
      <template path="templates/eval-gate.py" purpose="Pass/fail eval gate script using lm-eval harness"/>
      <template path="templates/axolotl.yaml" purpose="Axolotl YAML config for QLoRA fine-tuning"/>
    </templates>

